WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:13.070 --> 00:00:14.370
&gt;&gt; Charlotte Harper:
Everyone welcome.

00:00:14.370 --> 00:00:15.670
Thank you so much for coming.

00:00:15.670 --> 00:00:16.970
We really appreciate
you coming out.

00:00:16.970 --> 00:00:18.270
Who knew it was going to rain?

00:00:18.270 --> 00:00:22.200
I didn't. But you all did,
because you all have umbrellas.

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:23.740
Anyway, thank you for coming.

00:00:23.740 --> 00:00:25.040
I'm Charlotte Harper.

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:27.160
I'm the director of
programming here at Hill Center.

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:30.980
For how many of you is this
your first time at Hill Center?

00:00:30.980 --> 00:00:32.280
That's great.

00:00:32.280 --> 00:00:34.690
We love having events that bring
in new people, and it seems

00:00:34.690 --> 00:00:38.250
like this series, Life of
a Poet, with Ron Charles,

00:00:38.250 --> 00:00:39.740
is one of those series.

00:00:39.740 --> 00:00:44.420
We are so happy to have Ron and
the Library of Congress partner

00:00:44.420 --> 00:00:45.720
with us on this series.

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:47.950
We could not, obviously,
do this without them.

00:00:47.950 --> 00:00:50.300
We are thrilled, and
we are thrilled today

00:00:50.300 --> 00:00:54.970
to welcome Ross Gay and can't
wait to hear about his work.

00:00:54.970 --> 00:00:57.990
And by the way, his work
is being sold out here

00:00:57.990 --> 00:00:59.870
on the right-hand side
by East City Bookshop,

00:00:59.870 --> 00:01:04.140
a nice local bookshop,
women owned and operated.

00:01:04.140 --> 00:01:08.090
Yes. But right now, ID like
to turn it over to Rob Casper,

00:01:08.090 --> 00:01:10.200
the head of the Poetry
and Literature Center

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:11.500
at Library of Congress.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:13.300
So, give it up.

00:01:13.300 --> 00:01:17.070
[ Applause ]

00:01:17.070 --> 00:01:18.370
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: Hi everyone.

00:01:18.370 --> 00:01:19.670
Thanks for coming out.

00:01:19.670 --> 00:01:23.810
I'm curious how many
people came last week too?

00:01:23.810 --> 00:01:26.600
Wow, check you out.

00:01:26.600 --> 00:01:30.140
This weather is marginally
better than-- yeah, me too.

00:01:30.140 --> 00:01:35.280
Marginally better than last
week, but we hope you continue

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:39.090
to come to the series
as we do rain or shine.

00:01:39.090 --> 00:01:40.810
All right.

00:01:40.810 --> 00:01:45.680
I want to thank Charlotte and
everyone here at the Hill Center

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:47.670
for making this series possible.

00:01:47.670 --> 00:01:49.990
It's wonderful to be back
here in this great room

00:01:49.990 --> 00:01:52.220
with all of you tonight.

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:54.890
I also want to thank
The Washington Post

00:01:54.890 --> 00:01:58.750
and my personal hero,
Ron Charles.

00:01:59.870 --> 00:02:01.810
You know, two of these
conversations is a lot

00:02:01.810 --> 00:02:05.040
to take on in one week, but--

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:06.340
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I
was happy to do it.

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:07.640
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: And we're happy

00:02:07.640 --> 00:02:09.680
to have you here,
making it possible.

00:02:09.680 --> 00:02:10.980
Before I say anything more,

00:02:10.980 --> 00:02:13.380
I just want to tell you a
little bit about the poetry

00:02:13.380 --> 00:02:16.110
and literature center at
the Library of Congress.

00:02:16.110 --> 00:02:18.850
We are home to the Poet
Laureate Consultant in Poetry

00:02:18.850 --> 00:02:21.870
and in fact our poet
laureate, Tracy K. Smith,

00:02:21.870 --> 00:02:26.870
will be giving her closing event
on April 15, April 15, yeah.

00:02:26.870 --> 00:02:29.700
So you should come check
her out down the street

00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:32.110
at the Jefferson building.

00:02:32.110 --> 00:02:34.230
We also host a range
of programs.

00:02:34.230 --> 00:02:37.230
We'll have all sorts of programs
between now and April 15

00:02:37.230 --> 00:02:41.730
over at the Library's
Capitol Hill campus.

00:02:41.730 --> 00:02:43.920
If you want to find out
more about the Library,

00:02:43.920 --> 00:02:49.880
you should visit our
website, www.loc.gov/poetry.

00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:53.410
And we would really also
love to know what you think

00:02:53.410 --> 00:02:54.710
about tonight's program.

00:02:54.710 --> 00:02:57.440
On your seats, there
should be some surveys.

00:02:57.440 --> 00:02:59.130
If you could fill them
out, you can leave them

00:02:59.130 --> 00:03:00.430
on the chairs afterwards.

00:03:00.430 --> 00:03:01.820
You can hand them to me.

00:03:01.820 --> 00:03:03.770
We want to make sure
to get them and find

00:03:03.770 --> 00:03:06.220
out what we can do
better going forward.

00:03:06.220 --> 00:03:07.900
Though with Ron there's
not much we can do.

00:03:07.900 --> 00:03:10.420
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I filled
most of them out already.

00:03:12.130 --> 00:03:17.330
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: He said why does
that introducer go on so long.

00:03:17.330 --> 00:03:21.660
So, [inaudible] kicked off
our spring series last week.

00:03:21.660 --> 00:03:27.370
We're thrilled to have Ross Gay
here to end it a week later.

00:03:27.370 --> 00:03:31.060
If only winter was as short.

00:03:31.060 --> 00:03:34.320
Ross Gay is the author of
three books, Against Which,

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:38.580
Bringing the Shovel Down, and
Catalog of Unabashed Gratitude,

00:03:38.580 --> 00:03:41.860
winner of the 2015, National
Book Critic Circle Award

00:03:41.860 --> 00:03:46.020
and the 2016 Kingsley
Tuft's Award.

00:03:46.020 --> 00:03:48.330
Indeed. He is also
the founding editor

00:03:48.330 --> 00:03:51.720
of the online sports
magazine, Some Call it Ballin',

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:54.390
and an editor of the
Chapbook Press's Q Avenue

00:03:54.390 --> 00:03:56.920
and Ledge Mule Press.

00:03:56.920 --> 00:03:59.050
He is as well a founding
board member

00:03:59.050 --> 00:04:02.600
of the Bloomington Community
orchard, a nonprofit,

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:06.500
free-fruit-for-all food
justice and joy project,

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:08.280
which is a great description.

00:04:08.280 --> 00:04:11.080
He has received fellowships
from Cave Canem,

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:12.780
the Bread Loaf Writer's
Conference,

00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:15.180
and the Guggenheim Foundation.

00:04:15.180 --> 00:04:17.900
He is currently a professor
of English and director

00:04:17.900 --> 00:04:20.530
of the Creative Writing
Program at Indiana University

00:04:20.530 --> 00:04:22.410
in Bloomington where he lives.

00:04:22.410 --> 00:04:25.890
Of all the poets we have
featured in this series,

00:04:25.890 --> 00:04:29.940
Ross Gay has arguably
been the most anticipated.

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:32.970
This is partly due to the fact
that our dear Ron Charles served

00:04:32.970 --> 00:04:35.570
on the committee that awarded
Gay his National Book Critic

00:04:35.570 --> 00:04:37.060
Circle award for Catalog

00:04:37.060 --> 00:04:40.180
of Unabashed Gratitude
just a few years ago.

00:04:40.180 --> 00:04:42.000
The Washington Post,
and not Ron,

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.450
but Elizabeth Blunt called
Catalog, "A charming collection

00:04:47.450 --> 00:04:50.050
that gives readers
permission to feel joyful.

00:04:50.050 --> 00:04:54.010
Losses, small slights, and
large issues such as prejudice

00:04:54.010 --> 00:04:57.210
and violence also appear,
yet the speaker always tries

00:04:57.210 --> 00:04:59.010
to translate everything back

00:04:59.010 --> 00:05:01.700
into the original
language of possibility."

00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:04.830
Ron had the opportunity
to meet our future poet

00:05:04.830 --> 00:05:07.760
at the prize ceremony in
New York and hear him read,

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:11.200
and I believe he's been
smitten ever since.

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:14.470
I too have been struck by Ross
Gay's poems, which NPR says,

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:17.460
"burst forth in leggy,
unexpected ways,

00:05:17.460 --> 00:05:19.690
zooming in on legs
furred with pollen

00:05:19.690 --> 00:05:24.440
or soiled breasts
stroking into the xylem."

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:26.970
[laughter] Tess Taylor
had a lot more fun

00:05:26.970 --> 00:05:28.380
than [inaudible]
that description.

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:31.850
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I
didn't edit that.

00:05:31.850 --> 00:05:33.150
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: Though
Ross and I have never met,

00:05:33.150 --> 00:05:34.450
and I've never heard him read,

00:05:34.450 --> 00:05:36.480
I'll never forget the
day I read Catalog

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:38.800
of Unabashed Gratitude
cover to cover.

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:40.750
I was staying with
friends down in Austin,

00:05:40.750 --> 00:05:43.220
and I woke up one morning
to glorious sunlight pouring

00:05:43.220 --> 00:05:45.690
through the blinds of
my friend's office.

00:05:45.690 --> 00:05:46.990
In the course of getting up,

00:05:46.990 --> 00:05:48.910
my eye caught Gay's
third collection

00:05:48.910 --> 00:05:50.330
with its stunning cover art

00:05:50.330 --> 00:05:53.200
by Arista Alanis sitting
atop a pile of books.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:54.710
It's right here.

00:05:54.710 --> 00:05:57.750
I thought to myself, this has
been getting a lot of play,

00:05:57.750 --> 00:06:00.120
and picked it up with the
intent to simply leaf through

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:02.130
and then head to the
kitchen for breakfast.

00:06:02.130 --> 00:06:06.580
Well let me tell you, I did not
leave that room until I'd gone

00:06:06.580 --> 00:06:10.000
from To the Fig Tree on
Ninth and Christian straight

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.460
through to Last Will
and Testament,

00:06:12.460 --> 00:06:14.890
and I was good and
full of poetry.

00:06:14.890 --> 00:06:16.960
The same could be
said of what we're

00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:18.820
about to experience right now,

00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:22.970
and I'll bet you too won't ever
forget the magic of this moment.

00:06:22.970 --> 00:06:26.510
Please join me in welcoming
Ron Charles with Ross Gay.

00:06:26.510 --> 00:06:35.040
[ Applause ]

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:36.340
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I am
delighted you're here.

00:06:36.340 --> 00:06:37.640
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Thank
you, same here.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:38.940
And we get him first, you know.

00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:42.610
His new book comes out next
Tuesday, and here is the Book

00:06:42.610 --> 00:06:44.430
of Delights, and
it is delightful.

00:06:44.430 --> 00:06:45.730
It's not poetry.

00:06:45.730 --> 00:06:47.860
It's a selection of brief
essays that he said he wrote

00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:49.850
because the more
you study delights,

00:06:49.850 --> 00:06:52.680
the more delight
there is to study.

00:06:52.680 --> 00:06:54.380
My delight grows
when I share it.

00:06:54.380 --> 00:06:56.870
You will want to
get this, read it,

00:06:56.870 --> 00:06:59.630
and feel the delight
and the joy.

00:06:59.630 --> 00:07:01.710
In the middle of this piece,
I'm reading along, you know,

00:07:01.710 --> 00:07:07.880
enjoying them all, and at number
64, it's about poetry readings.

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:11.170
So I got to read, I got
to read from this again,

00:07:11.170 --> 00:07:14.380
but I did want him to read
a bit of this first essay

00:07:14.380 --> 00:07:16.800
to start us off, if you would.

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:18.100
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Totally.

00:07:18.100 --> 00:07:21.700
It's called, this title
was so hard to get right.

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:24.830
We really tried on this.

00:07:24.830 --> 00:07:29.320
It's called, number 64, fishing
an eyelash, two or three cents

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:31.170
on the virtues of
the poetry readings.

00:07:31.170 --> 00:07:36.130
It might be a kind of
self-aggrandizement to say so,

00:07:36.130 --> 00:07:38.100
but I love poetry readings.

00:07:38.100 --> 00:07:39.450
I love going to them.

00:07:39.450 --> 00:07:42.150
I think I love them, I probably
love them most often more

00:07:42.150 --> 00:07:43.520
than I love poetry books.

00:07:43.520 --> 00:07:45.520
I'm pretty sure this is true.

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:47.320
The reason is simple.

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:48.980
Because during a poetry reading,

00:07:48.980 --> 00:07:52.060
you're watching someone
communicate with their body,

00:07:52.060 --> 00:07:55.990
which is at it communicates
in the process of fading away.

00:07:55.990 --> 00:08:00.370
It will, perhaps one day
soon, be dead I mean.

00:08:00.370 --> 00:08:03.640
It sounds necrophilic, I
know, but it's not exactly.

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:06.760
Because the fact of the dying,
which too you and I will do,

00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:08.630
and which books will not,

00:08:08.630 --> 00:08:11.940
reminds us that the performing
body, the reading body,

00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:15.100
the living body, the body
fiddling with the reading lamp

00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:17.590
on the podium or playing
with the hem of her dress

00:08:17.590 --> 00:08:19.250
or keeping beat on
the microphone

00:08:19.250 --> 00:08:22.300
like Whitney Houston used
to, looking in the corners

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:25.350
of the room, the occasional
sparkling line of spit

00:08:25.350 --> 00:08:28.940
between his lips, the armpit
of their T-shirt damp,

00:08:28.940 --> 00:08:33.460
pointing to the giraffe in their
poem, all of it is illustrious.

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:35.260
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Nice.

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:40.140
[ Applause ]

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:43.940
There's a charming disruptive
self-consciousness in some

00:08:43.940 --> 00:08:46.840
of your poems when you
suddenly speak directly to us

00:08:46.840 --> 00:08:48.610
about the very act
of writing poems,

00:08:48.610 --> 00:08:49.910
if you know what
I'm talking about.

00:08:49.910 --> 00:08:51.210
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:08:51.210 --> 00:08:52.510
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yeah, yeah.

00:08:52.510 --> 00:08:53.810
In one poem you speak of burning
the world down to rebuild it,

00:08:53.810 --> 00:08:55.340
and then you stop and
admit, well that sounds

00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:57.400
like a bullshit poem
in the making.

00:08:57.400 --> 00:08:58.700
[laughter]

00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:00.000
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: That's right, yeah.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:01.410
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: And then,
in a poem called Come On,

00:09:01.410 --> 00:09:04.020
you describe your mother's
hands as the claws of a crab,

00:09:04.020 --> 00:09:07.110
and then you stop and say,
that's one of those poetry lies.

00:09:07.110 --> 00:09:11.070
What are the hallmarks
of a bullshit poem,

00:09:11.070 --> 00:09:12.870
and what are poetry lies?

00:09:12.870 --> 00:09:14.630
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: That's
a good question.

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:18.190
You know, maybe a great
story that I will tell is

00:09:18.190 --> 00:09:23.180
that my friend Evie was
talking about this poem

00:09:23.180 --> 00:09:26.330
where I say something
like that in the New Book,

00:09:26.330 --> 00:09:31.070
a poem called Fee, and I said
something about, you know,

00:09:31.070 --> 00:09:33.510
I love it when a poem says
I'm trying to do this,

00:09:33.510 --> 00:09:34.910
or I'm trying to do that.

00:09:34.910 --> 00:09:36.940
Sometimes it's a
horseshit trick.

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:39.730
But sometimes, and I sort of,
I think the poem needs to say,

00:09:39.730 --> 00:09:43.570
but sometimes like what
I'm doing, it's not.

00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:50.400
And Evie was like, sometimes I
think that's a horseshit trick.

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:55.100
So, anyway, what
was your question?

00:09:55.100 --> 00:09:56.400
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: So what are,

00:09:56.400 --> 00:09:58.890
what all right the
hallmarks of a bullshit poem?

00:09:58.890 --> 00:10:00.190
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Oh, yeah.

00:10:00.190 --> 00:10:02.030
God, I don't know.

00:10:02.030 --> 00:10:04.560
But I know in myself, like there
are moments where I'm trying

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:08.010
to sort of just do, do
a poemy thing, you know.

00:10:08.010 --> 00:10:09.310
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: A poemy thing?

00:10:09.310 --> 00:10:12.720
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, I'm trying to
do a poemy thing, and it's like,

00:10:12.720 --> 00:10:16.570
you know, sometimes it's a
real, honest attempt to get

00:10:16.570 --> 00:10:19.260
at some sort of genuine
feeling or something like that,

00:10:19.260 --> 00:10:21.210
and sometimes I'm
imitating the idea

00:10:21.210 --> 00:10:23.550
of what a poem feels
like somewhere.

00:10:23.550 --> 00:10:24.850
I think something like that.

00:10:24.850 --> 00:10:26.150
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You're
acting like a poet.

00:10:26.150 --> 00:10:27.450
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah,
yeah, yeah, totally.

00:10:27.450 --> 00:10:28.750
Like and I catch myself
periodically, like in that one

00:10:28.750 --> 00:10:32.220
where I'm, whatever I said
about my mom, and I'm like, eh,

00:10:32.220 --> 00:10:34.450
that's bullshit, you know.

00:10:34.450 --> 00:10:36.860
So, and I think it's kind
of fun to like leave it

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:38.580
in there sometimes
too and be like--

00:10:38.580 --> 00:10:39.880
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yes.

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:41.180
So we see the poem in the
process of becoming itself.

00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:42.480
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:10:42.480 --> 00:10:43.780
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It's great fun.

00:10:43.780 --> 00:10:45.080
You teach poetry?

00:10:45.080 --> 00:10:46.380
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:47.680
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You must
see a lot of bullshit poems.

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:48.980
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:10:48.980 --> 00:10:50.280
[laughter] Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:51.580
I mean no more from my students
than from myself though,

00:10:51.580 --> 00:10:52.880
to be perfectly honest.

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:54.750
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I want
you to read a poem called

00:10:54.750 --> 00:10:58.010
To the Mistake, in
your new collection.

00:10:58.010 --> 00:10:59.310
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:10:59.310 --> 00:11:02.090
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Which is called
Catalog of Unabashed Gratitude.

00:11:02.090 --> 00:11:04.640
To the Mistake.

00:11:04.640 --> 00:11:07.260
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: To the Mistake.

00:11:07.260 --> 00:11:10.780
It is good to know a
thing or two about that

00:11:10.780 --> 00:11:13.160
of which you speak,
or even to be expert,

00:11:13.160 --> 00:11:14.520
which is not requisite though.

00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:18.040
A thing or two is good, like
the prop plane I know is going

00:11:18.040 --> 00:11:21.720
to land on the canvas roof
of my friend's rickety jeep,

00:11:21.720 --> 00:11:25.530
while the salutatorian to be
sits in the back seat giddy

00:11:25.530 --> 00:11:27.720
with her new graphing
calculator.

00:11:27.720 --> 00:11:31.930
And the driver says something
I think about Arsenio Hall,

00:11:31.930 --> 00:11:33.510
and he sounds like a bunny.

00:11:33.510 --> 00:11:36.770
So, I don't know how
to do this poem really.

00:11:36.770 --> 00:11:38.170
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: What
are you doing?

00:11:38.170 --> 00:11:43.360
[laughter] You can just read the
poem, then we can talk about it.

00:11:43.360 --> 00:11:44.660
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: I know, I know.

00:11:44.660 --> 00:11:47.380
If it's better to
tell you before.

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:49.560
So the story is that
I made the error

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:53.580
of like taking acid
right before this reunion

00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:54.880
for the gifted class.

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:56.180
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You'll
get to that in the poem.

00:11:56.180 --> 00:11:57.480
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: I know,
I know, I know.

00:11:57.480 --> 00:12:00.280
But I don't, I don't
want you to miss it.

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:01.580
All right.

00:12:01.580 --> 00:12:02.880
You know the poem then.

00:12:02.880 --> 00:12:04.440
Just joking, just joking.

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:08.640
So, while the salutatorian to
be sits in the back seat giddy

00:12:08.640 --> 00:12:10.520
with her new graphing
calculator,

00:12:10.520 --> 00:12:14.070
and the driver says something,
I think, about Arsenio Hall,

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:17.260
and he sounds like a bunny in
an echo chamber, but it's hard

00:12:17.260 --> 00:12:19.730
to hear with those
propellers roaring above.

00:12:19.730 --> 00:12:22.780
And today, I am lecturing on
the miracle of the mistake

00:12:22.780 --> 00:12:26.490
in a poem, that hiccup or
weird gift that spirals

00:12:26.490 --> 00:12:29.420
or jettisons what's dull
and landlocked into as

00:12:29.420 --> 00:12:33.240
yet untraversed, i.e.,
cosmic, I overuse this metaphor

00:12:33.240 --> 00:12:35.460
with my students, grounds.

00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:40.500
I tell this to 105 give or take
undergrads who mostly don't care

00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:44.290
and wrestle second to second
the by now blood-borne drive

00:12:44.290 --> 00:12:47.270
to check their beckoning
phones, which mostly,

00:12:47.270 --> 00:12:48.970
bless them, they don't.

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:50.870
The mistake, I say, is a gift.

00:12:50.870 --> 00:12:52.170
Don't be afraid.

00:12:52.170 --> 00:12:54.760
See what it teaches you
about what the poem can be.

00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:56.560
I know of what I speak.

00:12:56.560 --> 00:13:01.030
Like the two tabs of very
potent, evidently acid I drop,

00:13:01.030 --> 00:13:04.870
four hours before this reunion
and graduation party of sorts

00:13:04.870 --> 00:13:09.020
for we, the gifted and talented,
corn chips and Mr. Pibb

00:13:09.020 --> 00:13:10.650
and store-bought cookies,

00:13:10.650 --> 00:13:14.270
the texture of which sunk
me knee deep in a dessert.

00:13:14.270 --> 00:13:18.200
I imagine I looked something
like an opaque cloud that day

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:21.740
when Mr. and Mrs.
Simonoski, our brainy hosts

00:13:21.740 --> 00:13:25.820
and teachers guffawed
acclamation, the tremendous bead

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:29.570
of spit balancing on Mr.
Simonoski's lip before a gust

00:13:29.570 --> 00:13:33.230
of air lifted it, and it
drifted to the coarse fabric

00:13:33.230 --> 00:13:36.650
of his beard, all the
spiny hairs of which seemed

00:13:36.650 --> 00:13:38.770
to screech like crickets.

00:13:38.770 --> 00:13:40.990
And no wonder I declined
the invitation

00:13:40.990 --> 00:13:44.320
from the volleyball court,
although I was a phys ed major.

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:47.640
And beneath the white arcs,
the ball painted in the sky,

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:50.680
my classmates, Lisa
and Eugene and Ick

00:13:50.680 --> 00:13:55.840
and Becky all looked a bit alien
with craniums engorged slightly

00:13:55.840 --> 00:13:59.180
and spines compressed
if not even serpentine,

00:13:59.180 --> 00:14:02.800
their limbs flailing about
wildly like cuttlefish,

00:14:02.800 --> 00:14:05.480
speaking only in poly-slavics

00:14:05.480 --> 00:14:09.400
which must have made my breathy
grunts all the more apish.

00:14:09.400 --> 00:14:11.540
Who knows where the
poem will lead you.

00:14:11.540 --> 00:14:14.610
I tell them to let go
their reigns and listen

00:14:14.610 --> 00:14:17.120
to the tongues half-wit
brilliance,

00:14:17.120 --> 00:14:21.160
the corner of the mind made
light by some accidental yoking

00:14:21.160 --> 00:14:25.550
of two impossibly joined
things, one or two in the rear.

00:14:25.550 --> 00:14:28.760
I notice their eyes roll into
the backs of their heads.

00:14:28.760 --> 00:14:30.560
And my plastic cup of root beer

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:33.870
by now is spilling a bit
while Mr. Simonoski laughs

00:14:33.870 --> 00:14:37.630
like a hyena, plunging
its face in a ruptured gut

00:14:37.630 --> 00:14:40.990
and nothing has ever been
as clear to me as the bell

00:14:40.990 --> 00:14:43.100
that rang in my head that day.

00:14:43.100 --> 00:14:46.210
We were a 12-year experiment.

00:14:46.210 --> 00:14:49.760
The garden variety brainiacs
from a suburban school,

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:53.190
passable genetic mixture,
forgettable location,

00:14:53.190 --> 00:14:55.850
Mr. Sim's oddly large eyes

00:14:55.850 --> 00:15:00.750
and his long reptilian tail now
making sense in the way someone

00:15:00.750 --> 00:15:03.550
with an electric can
opener voice seemed always

00:15:03.550 --> 00:15:08.300
to be inside him, speaking
when he spoke, now making sense

00:15:08.300 --> 00:15:10.990
as the night winds
down and the last

00:15:10.990 --> 00:15:13.030
of the cake is served writhing

00:15:13.030 --> 00:15:16.700
with some fluorescent
scrawl only I seem able

00:15:16.700 --> 00:15:19.680
to read while all the
good-natured kids whose

00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:24.090
fingernails are chewed raw and
jaws pulse who are so good,

00:15:24.090 --> 00:15:29.130
so very good, and soon will be
hauled into the bottomless sky

00:15:29.130 --> 00:15:30.630
under which I stumble

00:15:30.630 --> 00:15:34.990
to see what direction they're
coming from, and can I run.

00:15:34.990 --> 00:15:36.790
&gt;&gt; Wow.

00:15:36.790 --> 00:15:42.260
[ Applause ]

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:43.560
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: That is one

00:15:43.560 --> 00:15:46.170
of the most fun poems
about writing a poem.

00:15:46.170 --> 00:15:48.410
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:15:48.410 --> 00:15:50.950
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: The miracle
of the mistake in a poem,

00:15:50.950 --> 00:15:53.000
that hiccup or weird
gift that spirals

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.760
or jettisons what's
dull and land locked.

00:15:55.760 --> 00:15:57.340
The mistake, I say, is a gift.

00:15:57.340 --> 00:15:58.640
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:15:58.640 --> 00:16:02.450
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: What
do you mean by that?

00:16:02.450 --> 00:16:03.750
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Here I would

00:16:03.750 --> 00:16:05.560
like to reference Patrick
Rosow's [phonetic] essay,

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:07.160
The Art of the Mistake.

00:16:07.160 --> 00:16:12.300
And, you know, really it feels
to me like, so I'm going to talk

00:16:12.300 --> 00:16:13.910
about teaching, so much
of my teaching and so much

00:16:13.910 --> 00:16:16.490
of my writing life, like
when I'm discovering things,

00:16:16.490 --> 00:16:18.230
I feel like so often
I'm doing something

00:16:18.230 --> 00:16:19.790
that really feels accidental.

00:16:19.790 --> 00:16:23.720
It feels like I bump
into something, you know.

00:16:23.720 --> 00:16:28.750
So, the accident or the
mistake is the thing

00:16:28.750 --> 00:16:31.070
that I never would have
done, for whatever reason.

00:16:31.070 --> 00:16:32.370
I don't know how it gets there.

00:16:32.370 --> 00:16:35.640
Whatever, for whatever
reason something happens,

00:16:35.640 --> 00:16:39.610
and it is more true or
more like, you know,

00:16:39.610 --> 00:16:42.130
something is revealed in a
way that I could not have sort

00:16:42.130 --> 00:16:44.150
of willed myself to do.

00:16:44.150 --> 00:16:45.450
Something like that.

00:16:45.450 --> 00:16:46.750
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: And
you want your students

00:16:46.750 --> 00:16:48.140
to become self-conscious
of that process?

00:16:48.140 --> 00:16:51.760
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: I want to
sort of train all of us to,

00:16:51.760 --> 00:16:54.320
I mean when I'm talking to the
Intro to Creative Writing Class,

00:16:54.320 --> 00:16:56.830
which is, you know,
I just would be glad

00:16:56.830 --> 00:16:58.530
if they came every once
in a while, you know.

00:16:58.530 --> 00:16:59.830
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Right.

00:16:59.830 --> 00:17:03.450
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: But like when I'm
thinking about my, you know,

00:17:03.450 --> 00:17:06.070
further along students, I
am thinking about how is it

00:17:06.070 --> 00:17:10.700
that we can allow ourselves
or set up the conditions

00:17:10.700 --> 00:17:12.810
for ourselves to write things

00:17:12.810 --> 00:17:15.630
that we otherwise
could not have explored

00:17:15.630 --> 00:17:18.880
so that our knowledge itself
is not the sort of determining

00:17:18.880 --> 00:17:22.960
or predetermining sort of limit
of what we can make, you know.

00:17:22.960 --> 00:17:24.860
So we know something, but
then there's this other kind

00:17:24.860 --> 00:17:26.170
of knowing.

00:17:26.170 --> 00:17:29.310
And my hope as a teacher
and as a whatever,

00:17:29.310 --> 00:17:32.520
someone who makes stuff, is
that I'm able to sort of figure

00:17:32.520 --> 00:17:37.120
out how to bump into those other
kinds of knowing, you know?

00:17:37.120 --> 00:17:38.750
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yes, yeah.

00:17:38.750 --> 00:17:40.050
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Okay.

00:17:40.050 --> 00:17:41.350
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You describe
the poetry-making process

00:17:41.350 --> 00:17:42.780
in a variety of ways.

00:17:42.780 --> 00:17:44.520
In one poem called The Opening,

00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:45.820
there's this gorgeous
description

00:17:45.820 --> 00:17:48.570
of you pruning a peach tree.

00:17:48.570 --> 00:17:51.580
And you describe pruning away,
pruning away, pruning away,

00:17:51.580 --> 00:17:54.250
until you say the
air and the light

00:17:54.250 --> 00:17:56.000
and even a bird can
flow through it.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:57.300
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:17:57.300 --> 00:17:58.600
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It seems
to me you're talking about,

00:17:58.600 --> 00:17:59.980
among other things,
editing a poem.

00:17:59.980 --> 00:18:01.280
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:02.580
That's totally right.

00:18:02.580 --> 00:18:03.880
That's all right, hey.

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:05.180
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Not
at all, not at all.

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:06.480
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:18:06.480 --> 00:18:07.780
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: In The Spoon,
you write, I swear when I got

00:18:07.780 --> 00:18:09.470
into this poem I would convert
this sorrow into some kind

00:18:09.470 --> 00:18:13.040
of honey with a little music
that I can sometimes make

00:18:13.040 --> 00:18:16.830
with these scribbled
artifacts of our desolation.

00:18:16.830 --> 00:18:18.130
Tell us about that.

00:18:18.130 --> 00:18:21.100
Converting sorrow into honey.

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:24.170
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: That poem is so
like trying hard to make sense

00:18:24.170 --> 00:18:27.170
of something that
doesn't make sense.

00:18:27.170 --> 00:18:28.470
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It
says that in the poem.

00:18:28.470 --> 00:18:30.600
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah,
exactly, and--

00:18:30.600 --> 00:18:31.900
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: But I think many

00:18:31.900 --> 00:18:33.700
of your poems are making
honey out of sorrow.

00:18:33.700 --> 00:18:35.000
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:36.300
That's right.

00:18:36.300 --> 00:18:39.100
I think that was a poem
where I realized it more sort

00:18:39.100 --> 00:18:42.310
of profoundly than maybe
in some other poems.

00:18:42.310 --> 00:18:47.080
And yeah, it occurred to
me that often that the act

00:18:47.080 --> 00:18:49.050
of writing a poem, for me is
to make sense of something

00:18:49.050 --> 00:18:52.580
that doesn't make sense, or
maybe, I don't know, yeah,

00:18:52.580 --> 00:18:57.100
something like that, and
it arrived in that poem,

00:18:57.100 --> 00:19:00.430
that sort of thing of like,
oh, this is kind of what we do.

00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:04.030
This is kind of what we do,
like try to organize or order

00:19:04.030 --> 00:19:11.090
or make beautiful what
doesn't make sense, you know.

00:19:11.090 --> 00:19:15.590
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: The honey sounds
sweet, risk being saccharine,

00:19:15.590 --> 00:19:18.230
your poem is taking
on some really,

00:19:18.230 --> 00:19:21.210
really tough, horrible issues.

00:19:21.210 --> 00:19:24.020
They are not sweet
poems, generally.

00:19:24.020 --> 00:19:25.320
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:19:25.320 --> 00:19:26.620
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: The
scribbled artifacts

00:19:26.620 --> 00:19:29.820
of our desolation are really
clear in some of these poems.

00:19:29.820 --> 00:19:33.250
Would you read a poem called For
a Young Emergency Room Doctor?

00:19:33.250 --> 00:19:35.550
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:43.340
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Take
the tab out.

00:19:43.340 --> 00:19:44.640
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:46.590
For a Young Emergency
Room Doctor.

00:19:46.590 --> 00:19:49.460
Although this prayer should
first dress the dead boy's

00:19:49.460 --> 00:19:54.320
wounds, nine gunshots, in
and out, the spine pierced

00:19:54.320 --> 00:19:58.210
and wrecked enough to twist
the head dangled backward,

00:19:58.210 --> 00:20:02.520
and before the body, the night
through which the bullet chewed,

00:20:02.520 --> 00:20:05.480
and the latex sheathing the
hands of the cops who dragged

00:20:05.480 --> 00:20:07.700
and dropped the boy
on the gurney,

00:20:07.700 --> 00:20:12.270
last touch of this world
gloved, and the heart's dirge,

00:20:12.270 --> 00:20:16.150
dwindling lament for
spilled blood, lost love too,

00:20:16.150 --> 00:20:19.090
for the blankets of
light wrapping him,

00:20:19.090 --> 00:20:23.230
jeweling the viscous
liquid slicking his lips.

00:20:23.230 --> 00:20:25.490
It's for the living, for those

00:20:25.490 --> 00:20:28.980
who close the boy's
eyes again and again.

00:20:28.980 --> 00:20:33.650
For whom salve is the
wound's mend, the eased bleed,

00:20:33.650 --> 00:20:36.100
who tell the story while eating,

00:20:36.100 --> 00:20:39.970
who too die at the
dying's rising pile.

00:20:46.120 --> 00:20:50.320
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Is this written
from some personal experience?

00:20:50.320 --> 00:20:51.690
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, this
is my best, you know,

00:20:51.690 --> 00:20:54.900
one of my best friend's is
an ER doctor, and we were in,

00:20:54.900 --> 00:20:59.000
I was getting my PhD in English
while he was in med school.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:02.630
So we were living
together, and I was sort

00:21:02.630 --> 00:21:05.480
of with him while
he was in training.

00:21:05.480 --> 00:21:10.900
So, you know, he was
encountering all kinds of,

00:21:10.900 --> 00:21:12.200
you know, [inaudible].

00:21:12.200 --> 00:21:14.580
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It's incredibly
common for ER doctors.

00:21:14.580 --> 00:21:15.880
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah,
yeah, totally.

00:21:15.880 --> 00:21:17.180
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: What
city was this in?

00:21:17.180 --> 00:21:18.480
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Philly.

00:21:18.480 --> 00:21:19.780
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yeah.

00:21:19.780 --> 00:21:21.080
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:21:21.080 --> 00:21:23.040
I haven't read that
poem in a long time.

00:21:23.040 --> 00:21:25.980
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Here's
another poem called the Bullet

00:21:25.980 --> 00:21:27.280
in Its Hunger.

00:21:27.280 --> 00:21:28.670
It's number four.

00:21:28.670 --> 00:21:31.270
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:21:31.270 --> 00:21:33.790
The Bullet in Its Hunger.

00:21:35.750 --> 00:21:40.800
The bullet in its hunger
craves the womb of the body,

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:42.900
the warmth from there.

00:21:42.900 --> 00:21:47.330
Begs always release from
the chilly dumb chamber.

00:21:47.330 --> 00:21:50.920
Look at this one who's glee
at escape was out shown only

00:21:50.920 --> 00:21:53.390
by the heavens above him.

00:21:53.390 --> 00:21:57.740
The night's even-keeled breath,
all things thus far dreams

00:21:57.740 --> 00:22:00.040
from his cramped bunker.

00:22:00.040 --> 00:22:02.800
But now, the world.

00:22:02.800 --> 00:22:06.270
Let me be a ravenous
diamond in it, he thinks,

00:22:06.270 --> 00:22:08.110
chewing through the
milky jaw bone

00:22:08.110 --> 00:22:11.180
of this handsome 17-year-old.

00:22:11.180 --> 00:22:12.600
Of course, he would have loved

00:22:12.600 --> 00:22:15.670
to nestle amidst the brain's
scintillant catacombs,

00:22:15.670 --> 00:22:19.750
which only for the boy's
dumb luck slipped away,

00:22:19.750 --> 00:22:21.430
but this will do.

00:22:21.430 --> 00:22:25.250
The bullet does not, as
the boy goes into shock,

00:22:25.250 --> 00:22:28.720
or as his best friend
stutters, palming fluid wound,

00:22:28.720 --> 00:22:32.200
want to know the nature of
the conflict, nor the sound

00:22:32.200 --> 00:22:34.290
of the shooter's
mother in prayer,

00:22:34.290 --> 00:22:37.200
nor the shot child's
future harmonies,

00:22:37.200 --> 00:22:39.270
the tracheostomy's
muffled wheeze,

00:22:39.270 --> 00:22:41.000
threaded thru the
pencil's whisper

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:44.350
as the boy scrawls unscarred.

00:22:44.350 --> 00:22:51.850
No. The bullet, like you, simply
craves the warmth of the body.

00:22:51.850 --> 00:22:55.930
Like you, only wants to
die in someone's arms.

00:22:55.930 --> 00:23:03.200
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: That's an
incredibly unnerving poem.

00:23:03.200 --> 00:23:08.180
And paired with the other
one, there's nothing as sweet

00:23:08.180 --> 00:23:10.050
or honey, nothing
was transformed

00:23:10.050 --> 00:23:12.680
into honey in those poems.

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:14.120
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:16.070
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: What
inspires poems about that kind

00:23:16.070 --> 00:23:20.460
of endemic American violence?

00:23:20.460 --> 00:23:25.550
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: I guess trying to
figure out like some [inaudible]

00:23:25.550 --> 00:23:30.370
to think about what feels
like such a profound failure

00:23:30.370 --> 00:23:33.710
of the imagination, you know.

00:23:33.710 --> 00:23:39.230
It just feels, you know,
some way of talking

00:23:39.230 --> 00:23:44.080
about how this is, how this is
even possible among, you know,

00:23:44.080 --> 00:23:46.180
like people who ostensively care

00:23:46.180 --> 00:23:49.060
for each other or
can, you know--

00:23:49.060 --> 00:23:55.690
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Like why
it would become normal

00:23:55.690 --> 00:23:59.640
to lose 85 people a
day to gun violence.

00:23:59.640 --> 00:24:00.940
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Exactly.

00:24:00.940 --> 00:24:02.240
It's just a thing.

00:24:02.240 --> 00:24:04.410
It's just what it is.

00:24:04.410 --> 00:24:08.760
It's, you know, it's, and you
know, of course, you talk to,

00:24:08.760 --> 00:24:10.890
you know, it's fucking crazy.

00:24:10.890 --> 00:24:12.190
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yeah.

00:24:12.190 --> 00:24:13.490
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: It's fucking crazy.

00:24:13.490 --> 00:24:15.030
And I guess in a way the poem
is just trying to be like,

00:24:15.030 --> 00:24:19.310
you know, I don't even know,
like trying to just further sort

00:24:19.310 --> 00:24:24.550
of contend with the craziness.

00:24:24.550 --> 00:24:26.610
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Well, it
upsets our apathy, I think.

00:24:26.610 --> 00:24:27.910
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:24:27.910 --> 00:24:31.650
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It's so creepy
