00:25:55.510 --> 00:25:59.910
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah,
yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:25:59.910 --> 00:26:03.270
Yeah. Pulled Over In
Short Hills of New Jersey

00:26:03.270 --> 00:26:10.310
at 8 a.m. It's the shivering,
when rage grows hot as an army

00:26:10.310 --> 00:26:12.310
of red ants and forces the mind

00:26:12.310 --> 00:26:15.730
to quiet the body,
the quakes emerge.

00:26:15.730 --> 00:26:20.550
Sometimes just the knees, but at
worst, through the hips, chest,

00:26:20.550 --> 00:26:24.800
neck, until like a virus,
slipping inside the lungs

00:26:24.800 --> 00:26:29.000
and pulse, every ounce of
strength tapped to squeeze words

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:33.280
from my taut lips, his eyes
scanning my car's insides,

00:26:33.280 --> 00:26:37.420
my eyes, my license, and as I
answer the questions, three,

00:26:37.420 --> 00:26:41.200
four, five times, my
jaw tight as a vice,

00:26:41.200 --> 00:26:45.510
his hand massaging the gun butt,
I imagine things I don't want to

00:26:45.510 --> 00:26:46.850
and inside beg this

00:26:46.850 --> 00:26:49.760
to end before the shiver
catches my hands and he sees

00:26:49.760 --> 00:26:52.060
and something happens.

00:27:01.040 --> 00:27:04.150
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I have had
you read these brutal poems.

00:27:04.150 --> 00:27:05.450
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:27:05.450 --> 00:27:07.340
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Because we're
about to talk about gratitude,

00:27:07.340 --> 00:27:12.190
and I want your audience to
know that you have contended

00:27:12.190 --> 00:27:17.050
with the most horrible
aspects of life

00:27:17.050 --> 00:27:21.390
and still somehow
persist in joy.

00:27:21.390 --> 00:27:25.820
And it's the most
remarkable thing about you.

00:27:25.820 --> 00:27:27.470
In some of your poems, we can
see you moving back and forth

00:27:27.470 --> 00:27:28.800
between the light and horror

00:27:28.800 --> 00:27:31.380
in really surprising
unsettling ways.

00:27:31.380 --> 00:27:32.680
Grief to joy.

00:27:32.680 --> 00:27:34.340
It's a signature maneuver
in some of your poems.

00:27:34.340 --> 00:27:35.640
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:27:35.640 --> 00:27:37.560
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Would
you read Ode to Buttoning

00:27:37.560 --> 00:27:38.860
and Unbuttoning My Shirt?

00:27:38.860 --> 00:27:40.160
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:27:40.160 --> 00:27:41.460
Yeah.

00:27:41.460 --> 00:27:42.760
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Seven.

00:27:42.760 --> 00:27:44.060
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:27:44.060 --> 00:27:45.360
I had such a nice
time last night.

00:27:45.360 --> 00:27:46.660
I was reading at Villanova,
and a couple of these,

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:50.170
a couple students had read the
book, and they were talking

00:27:50.170 --> 00:27:52.520
about this poem and they were,
when they were talking to me,

00:27:52.520 --> 00:27:56.720
they were sort of like
buttoning and unbuttoning.

00:27:56.720 --> 00:27:58.860
[laughter] It was great.

00:27:58.860 --> 00:28:02.880
Ode to Buttoning and
Unbuttoning my Shirt.

00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:07.400
No one knew or at least I
didn't know they knew-- no.

00:28:07.400 --> 00:28:10.390
No one knew or at least I didn't
know they knew what the thin

00:28:10.390 --> 00:28:14.750
disks threaded here on my shirt
might give me in terms of joy.

00:28:14.750 --> 00:28:17.370
This is not something
to be taken lightly.

00:28:17.370 --> 00:28:21.020
The gift of buttoning one's
shirt, slowly top to bottom,

00:28:21.020 --> 00:28:24.170
or bottom to top or
sometimes the buttons will be

00:28:24.170 --> 00:28:26.630
on the other side, and I
am a woman that morning,

00:28:26.630 --> 00:28:28.900
slipping the glass
through its slot.

00:28:28.900 --> 00:28:32.120
I tread differently that
day, or some of it anyway.

00:28:32.120 --> 00:28:33.530
My conversations are different.

00:28:33.530 --> 00:28:36.220
And the car bombs slicing
the air and the people in it

00:28:36.220 --> 00:28:39.510
for a quarter mile and the
honey bee's legs furred

00:28:39.510 --> 00:28:42.220
with pollen mean another thing
to me than on the other days,

00:28:42.220 --> 00:28:45.550
which too have been drizzled
in this simplest of joys,

00:28:45.550 --> 00:28:49.860
in this world of spaceships and
subatomic this and that, two,

00:28:49.860 --> 00:28:51.700
maybe three times
a day some days,

00:28:51.700 --> 00:28:55.790
I have the distinct pleasure of
slowly untethering the one side

00:28:55.790 --> 00:28:58.970
from the other, which is
like unbuckling a stack

00:28:58.970 --> 00:29:01.350
of vertebrae with delicacy.

00:29:01.350 --> 00:29:04.460
For I must only use
the tips of my fingers,

00:29:04.460 --> 00:29:08.460
with which I will one day
close my mother's eyes.

00:29:08.460 --> 00:29:12.010
This is as delicate as
we can be in this life,

00:29:12.010 --> 00:29:15.800
practicing like this,
giving the raft of our hands

00:29:15.800 --> 00:29:18.660
to the clumsy spider
and blowing soft

00:29:18.660 --> 00:29:21.870
until she lifts her damp
heft and crawls off.

00:29:21.870 --> 00:29:26.340
We practice like this, pushing
seed into the earth like this,

00:29:26.340 --> 00:29:29.200
first in the morning,
then at night,

00:29:29.200 --> 00:29:32.590
we practice sliding
the bones home.

00:29:32.590 --> 00:29:34.390
&gt;&gt; Wow.

00:29:34.390 --> 00:29:38.110
[ Applause ]

00:29:38.110 --> 00:29:40.440
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: So lovely, and
you hear that movement back

00:29:40.440 --> 00:29:43.140
and forth, and it's
surprising each time, right.

00:29:43.140 --> 00:29:45.310
It starts so light, funny.

00:29:45.310 --> 00:29:47.180
This is not to be taken
lightly, the pleasure

00:29:47.180 --> 00:29:48.480
of buttoning my shirt.

00:29:48.480 --> 00:29:49.780
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:29:49.780 --> 00:29:51.080
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yeah.

00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:53.050
And then, the car bomb
suddenly slices the air.

00:29:53.050 --> 00:29:54.790
And those delicate fingers

00:29:54.790 --> 00:29:57.090
with the buttons are
