00:30:02.500 --> 00:30:05.240
It's surprising,
again and again.

00:30:05.240 --> 00:30:06.900
Would you read a
poem called Feet?

00:30:06.900 --> 00:30:08.670
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Oh, yeah.

00:30:08.670 --> 00:30:11.280
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: This also
feels so light and funny.

00:30:11.280 --> 00:30:13.610
It's not just me.

00:30:13.610 --> 00:30:14.910
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:30:14.910 --> 00:30:20.770
Feet. The things that
you might need to know is

00:30:20.770 --> 00:30:29.050
that the Real World was a, maybe
it is a show still on a MTV?

00:30:29.050 --> 00:30:30.350
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: This
looks like an MTV crowd.

00:30:30.350 --> 00:30:31.650
[laughter]

00:30:31.650 --> 00:30:34.540
&gt;&gt; They canceled it.

00:30:34.540 --> 00:30:36.420
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Oh, they
cancel, okay thank you.

00:30:36.420 --> 00:30:37.720
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Thank
you, young person.

00:30:37.720 --> 00:30:39.580
[laughter]

00:30:39.580 --> 00:30:40.920
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Thank you.

00:30:40.920 --> 00:30:46.570
Yeah. And the other one
is Powerman and Iron Fist.

00:30:46.570 --> 00:30:47.950
So that's a comic book.

00:30:47.950 --> 00:30:49.830
Luke Cage is Powerman.

00:30:49.830 --> 00:30:55.010
Powerman and Iron Fist, that was
what I read when I was a kid.

00:30:55.010 --> 00:31:00.100
Feet. Friends, mine
are ugly feet.

00:31:00.100 --> 00:31:03.770
The body's common wreckage
stuffed into boots.

00:31:03.770 --> 00:31:06.640
The second toe on the left
foot is crooked enough

00:31:06.640 --> 00:31:11.250
that when a child asks what's
that of it, I can without flinch

00:31:11.250 --> 00:31:14.580
or fear of doubt lie
that a cow stepped on it,

00:31:14.580 --> 00:31:18.620
which maybe makes them fear
cows, for which I repent.

00:31:18.620 --> 00:31:21.310
In love as I am with those
philosophical beasts,

00:31:21.310 --> 00:31:23.510
who would never smash
my feet nor sneer

00:31:23.510 --> 00:31:26.090
at them the way my mother does.

00:31:26.090 --> 00:31:29.310
We always bought you good
shoes, honey, she says.

00:31:29.310 --> 00:31:31.900
You can't blame us
for those things.

00:31:31.900 --> 00:31:33.600
And for this, and other--

00:31:33.600 --> 00:31:35.730
my mom has been in a crowd
like when I've read that poem,

00:31:35.730 --> 00:31:37.160
and she loses her
mind at that line.

00:31:37.160 --> 00:31:40.120
She like falls out
of her seat laughing.

00:31:40.120 --> 00:31:43.190
And for this and other
reasons, I have never indulged

00:31:43.190 --> 00:31:47.430
in the pleasure of flip flops,
shy or ashamed, digging my toes

00:31:47.430 --> 00:31:51.260
like ten tiny ostriches into the
sand at the beach with friends,

00:31:51.260 --> 00:31:53.670
who I'm not sure love me.

00:31:53.670 --> 00:31:55.290
Though I don't think
Tina loved me.

00:31:55.290 --> 00:31:58.770
She liked me I think,
but said to me,

00:31:58.770 --> 00:32:02.150
as we sat on lawn chairs beside
a pool where I lifeguarded

00:32:02.150 --> 00:32:05.150
and was meticulous at
obscuring from view with a book

00:32:05.150 --> 00:32:09.620
or towel my screwy friends,
you have pretty feet.

00:32:09.620 --> 00:32:12.900
In that gaudy, cement
mixer, Levittown accent

00:32:12.900 --> 00:32:16.730
that sends all the lemurs
scaling my rib cage to see,

00:32:16.730 --> 00:32:19.220
and she actually
had pretty feet.

00:32:19.220 --> 00:32:21.510
So I took this as a
kindness, incomparable

00:32:21.510 --> 00:32:23.600
and probably fell a
little bit in love with her

00:32:23.600 --> 00:32:27.210
for that afternoon, with the
weird white streak in her hair

00:32:27.210 --> 00:32:30.480
and her machine gun chatter
and her gums snapping,

00:32:30.480 --> 00:32:33.760
and so I slid my feet
from beneath my Powerman

00:32:33.760 --> 00:32:37.740
and Iron Fist comic book into
the sun for which they acted

00:32:37.740 --> 00:32:41.950
like plants, open their tiny
mouths to the food hurtling

00:32:41.950 --> 00:32:44.100
to them through the
solar system.

00:32:44.100 --> 00:32:47.010
And like plants, you could
watch them almost smile,

00:32:47.010 --> 00:32:49.040
almost say thank you.

00:32:49.040 --> 00:32:52.130
You could watch them turn
colors and be almost emboldened,

00:32:52.130 --> 00:32:54.780
none of which Tina saw,
because she was probably digging

00:32:54.780 --> 00:32:58.180
in her purse, or talking about
that hotty on the Real World

00:32:58.180 --> 00:33:00.720
or yelling at some friend's
little sister to put her ass

00:33:00.720 --> 00:33:03.080
in her trunks or pouring
the crumbs of her Fritos

00:33:03.080 --> 00:33:04.770
into her thrown open mouth,

00:33:04.770 --> 00:33:07.540
but do you really think I'm
talking to you about my feet?

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:11.440
Of course she's dead.

00:33:11.440 --> 00:33:17.390
Tina was her name, of
leukemia, so I heard.

00:33:17.390 --> 00:33:19.820
Why else would I try
sadly to make music

00:33:19.820 --> 00:33:21.690
of her unremarkable kindness?

00:33:21.690 --> 00:33:25.460
I'm trying, I think,
to forgive myself

00:33:25.460 --> 00:33:28.730
for something, I
don't know what.

00:33:28.730 --> 00:33:31.090
But what I do know is
that I love the moment

00:33:31.090 --> 00:33:33.770
when the poet says
I'm trying to do this

00:33:33.770 --> 00:33:36.350
or I'm trying to do that.

00:33:36.350 --> 00:33:40.400
Sometimes it's a horseshit
trick, but sometimes it's a way

00:33:40.400 --> 00:33:44.220
by which the poet says I
wish I could tell you truly

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:48.750
of the little factory in my
head, the smokestacks chuffing,

00:33:48.750 --> 00:33:51.240
the dandelions and
purslane and willows

00:33:51.240 --> 00:33:54.930
of sweet clover prying
through the blacktop.

00:33:54.930 --> 00:33:58.160
I wish I could tell you how
inside is the steady mumble

00:33:58.160 --> 00:34:02.020
and clank of machines, but
mostly, I wish I could tell you

00:34:02.020 --> 00:34:06.270
of the footsteps I hear,
more than I can ever count,

00:34:06.270 --> 00:34:11.480
all of whose gaits I can
discern by listening closely,

00:34:11.480 --> 00:34:16.230
which promptly disappear after
being lodged again, here,

00:34:16.230 --> 00:34:18.580
where we started, in the factory

00:34:18.580 --> 00:34:22.010
where loss makes all
things beautiful grow.

