It's just like these different
ways of sort trying to sort

00:48:48.150 --> 00:48:54.140
of contend with this absence and
this sorry and this, you know,

00:48:54.140 --> 00:48:58.700
illness that had led
up to it and all this.

00:48:58.700 --> 00:49:00.440
And that's one of them.

00:49:00.440 --> 00:49:03.130
I mean one of the thing that
I sort of was getting a kick

00:49:03.130 --> 00:49:06.140
out of reading the poem is
how much it's in the mouth.

00:49:06.140 --> 00:49:10.450
It's so like chewy, you know.

00:49:10.450 --> 00:49:13.570
Like all those words, and
it kind of makes me glad

00:49:13.570 --> 00:49:18.020
to remember, again Tom Lux and
other people, how much a kind

00:49:18.020 --> 00:49:23.080
of like leaning on
language is going on.

00:49:23.080 --> 00:49:27.560
And it's just like the erotic,
it's the erotics of the music

00:49:27.560 --> 00:49:30.580
in the mouth, you know,
is sort of happening.

00:49:30.580 --> 00:49:32.770
So that even saying it,
it's like your mouth has

00:49:32.770 --> 00:49:36.490
to do all these sorts
of, you know, things.

00:49:36.490 --> 00:49:37.790
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Right.

00:49:37.790 --> 00:49:41.560
It pushes back against death
even in memorializing it.

00:49:41.560 --> 00:49:42.860
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Totally, yeah.

00:49:42.860 --> 00:49:44.160
It's like music.

00:49:44.160 --> 00:49:45.460
You know, you dance.

00:49:45.460 --> 00:49:46.760
That's it.

00:49:46.760 --> 00:49:48.060
You know.

00:49:48.060 --> 00:49:49.360
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: In one
poem you say dance is one

00:49:49.360 --> 00:49:50.660
of the things you
happen to do pretty well.

00:49:50.660 --> 00:49:51.960
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:49:51.960 --> 00:49:53.260
Yeah. [laughter]

00:49:53.260 --> 00:49:55.560
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yeah.

00:50:06.170 --> 00:50:07.490
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: I love that,
even though I don't know it,

00:50:07.490 --> 00:50:10.180
I love that Mary
Tyler Moore reference.

00:50:11.210 --> 00:50:14.030
[laughter] That was
totally curveball.

00:50:14.030 --> 00:50:16.330
That's great.

00:50:21.180 --> 00:50:23.200
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: The
poem called Overheard.

00:50:23.200 --> 00:50:25.710
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Um, yeah.

00:50:25.710 --> 00:50:27.010
Overheard.

00:50:27.010 --> 00:50:34.070
It's a beautiful day the
small man said from behind me,

00:50:34.070 --> 00:50:37.050
and I could tell he had a slight
limp from the rasp of his boot

00:50:37.050 --> 00:50:40.600
against the sidewalk, and
I was slow to look at him,

00:50:40.600 --> 00:50:43.400
because I've learned to close
my ears against the voices

00:50:43.400 --> 00:50:45.680
of passersby, which is easier

00:50:45.680 --> 00:50:48.380
than closing them
to my own mind.

00:50:48.380 --> 00:50:50.150
And although he said
it, I did not hear it

00:50:50.150 --> 00:50:52.670
until he said it a second
or third time, but he did.

00:50:52.670 --> 00:50:55.830
He said, it's a beautiful day.

00:50:55.830 --> 00:50:59.090
And something in the way he
pointed to the sun unfolding

00:50:59.090 --> 00:51:01.970
between two oaks
overhanging a basketball court

00:51:01.970 --> 00:51:05.780
on Tenth Street made me too
catch hold of that light,

00:51:05.780 --> 00:51:08.950
opening my hands to the
dream of the soon blooming,

00:51:08.950 --> 00:51:10.690
and never did he
say forget the crick

00:51:10.690 --> 00:51:13.820
in your neck nor
your bloody dreams.

00:51:13.820 --> 00:51:16.070
He did not say forget
the multiple shades

00:51:16.070 --> 00:51:19.160
of your mother's heartbreak
nor the father in your city,

00:51:19.160 --> 00:51:21.490
kneeling over his bloody child.

00:51:21.490 --> 00:51:25.090
Nor the five species of bird
this second become memory.

00:51:25.090 --> 00:51:29.730
No, he said only it's a
beautiful day, this tiny man,

00:51:29.730 --> 00:51:32.370
limping past me with
upturned palms,

00:51:32.370 --> 00:51:35.510
shaking his head in disbelief.

00:51:35.510 --> 00:51:38.510
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:51:38.510 --> 00:51:43.890
[ Applause ]

00:51:43.890 --> 00:51:45.220
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: That old man--

00:51:45.220 --> 00:51:46.520
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:51:46.520 --> 00:51:47.820
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: In
that one phrase,

00:51:47.820 --> 00:51:49.780
in that act of recognizing
the beauty

00:51:49.780 --> 00:51:54.400
of the day does everything
your palms do.

00:51:54.400 --> 00:51:57.230
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah,
that's it, that's it.

00:51:57.230 --> 00:52:02.530
I was just thinking like,
oh, that's an ethics.

00:52:02.530 --> 00:52:06.570
And I think probably, you
know, like that's one of the,

00:52:06.570 --> 00:52:08.970
one of the teachers of,
for me, of an ethics

00:52:08.970 --> 00:52:11.250
that I aspire to, I think, yeah.

00:52:11.250 --> 00:52:12.550
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Not
Pollyannaish,

00:52:12.550 --> 00:52:15.650
not ignoring anything,
not denying anything bad,

00:52:15.650 --> 00:52:17.210
recognizes all the bad things.

00:52:17.210 --> 00:52:18.510
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:52:18.510 --> 00:52:19.810
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It can also
still be a beautiful day.

00:52:19.810 --> 00:52:21.110
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:52:21.110 --> 00:52:22.410
Totally.

00:52:22.410 --> 00:52:25.760
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You're
totally into gardening.

00:52:25.760 --> 00:52:27.770
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, big time.

00:52:27.770 --> 00:52:29.070
Yeah.

00:52:29.070 --> 00:52:30.370
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: And
it's an adult passion.

00:52:30.370 --> 00:52:32.610
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, I
learned, I started gardening,

00:52:32.610 --> 00:52:36.040
I mean like really gardening
in a garden where I live

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:39.930
in the last 11 years, yeah.

00:52:39.930 --> 00:52:43.130
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It is
or you have made it

00:52:43.130 --> 00:52:45.490
into a perfect metaphor
for your work.

00:52:45.490 --> 00:52:46.790
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:52:46.790 --> 00:52:48.090
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Everything dies.

00:52:48.090 --> 00:52:49.390
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:52:49.390 --> 00:52:51.650
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: And new life
springs up from those things.

00:52:51.650 --> 00:52:52.950
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:52:52.950 --> 00:52:54.250
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: And
pushed dead-looking things

00:52:54.250 --> 00:52:55.550
into the ground, and
life comes out of it.

00:52:55.550 --> 00:52:56.850
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah,
yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:52:56.850 --> 00:52:58.150
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It's a miracle

00:52:58.150 --> 00:52:59.450
that your poems again
and again reenact.

00:52:59.450 --> 00:53:01.750
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Right, right, yeah.

00:53:04.600 --> 00:53:08.260
And the garden is like this
bounty, like this bounty,

00:53:08.260 --> 00:53:13.730
like this bounty of sort of,
you know, like it's so full

00:53:13.730 --> 00:53:18.380
of wonder and incomprehensible
like happenings, you know.

00:53:18.380 --> 00:53:19.680
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yes.

00:53:19.680 --> 00:53:21.540
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Like there's so
much going on in a garden,

00:53:21.540 --> 00:53:24.180
which is part of why
I remain fascinated,

00:53:24.180 --> 00:53:28.210
and I think I'll probably never
not be fascinated by the garden

00:53:28.210 --> 00:53:29.830
because I will come
upon something,

00:53:29.830 --> 00:53:32.860
and I'll be like,
what are you doing?

00:53:32.860 --> 00:53:35.100
You know, what is happening?

00:53:35.100 --> 00:53:39.640
Like how is it that this many
pollinators are swirling around?

00:53:39.640 --> 00:53:43.190
Like I can't get my head
around it, you know.

00:53:43.190 --> 00:53:45.600
And that feels, that
feels wonderful.

00:53:45.600 --> 00:53:50.540
Like there is this cycle, this
utterly necessary cycle going

00:53:50.540 --> 00:53:52.600
on that I can witness and be

00:53:52.600 --> 00:53:55.880
like that's fucking
beautiful and--

00:53:57.900 --> 00:53:59.200
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Miraculous.

00:53:59.200 --> 00:54:00.500
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yes, yes, yes.

00:54:00.500 --> 00:54:01.800
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You have
so many great references

00:54:01.800 --> 00:54:03.100
in your poems to bees.

00:54:03.100 --> 00:54:04.400
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:54:04.400 --> 00:54:05.700
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Bumblebees.

00:54:05.700 --> 00:54:07.000
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah.

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:09.320
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Bees coming out
of flowers covered in pollen.

00:54:09.320 --> 00:54:12.170
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:54:12.170 --> 00:54:13.950
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Confused
and drunk.

00:54:13.950 --> 00:54:15.330
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:54:15.330 --> 00:54:16.830
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You have a
gorgeous poem called burial

00:54:16.830 --> 00:54:25.250
about using your own father's,
using your own father's ashes

00:54:25.250 --> 00:54:28.410
as fertilizer for your plums.

00:54:28.410 --> 00:54:33.230
Could you read that for us?

00:54:33.230 --> 00:54:34.560
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:54:34.560 --> 00:54:35.860
Of course.

00:54:35.860 --> 00:54:37.160
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Mark 14.

00:54:37.160 --> 00:54:38.460
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yep.

00:54:38.460 --> 00:54:44.110
So when I read this,
I need to ask

00:54:44.110 --> 00:54:47.180
if anyone has done
anything with placenta?

00:54:47.180 --> 00:54:49.350
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:54:49.350 --> 00:54:50.730
What have you done with
a placenta, if I may?

00:54:50.730 --> 00:54:54.040
&gt;&gt; I buried it under a tree in
our back garden, a cherry tree

00:54:54.040 --> 00:54:55.340
that I love very much.

00:54:55.340 --> 00:54:56.640
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Okay, great.

00:54:56.640 --> 00:54:57.940
Yeah, yeah.

00:54:57.940 --> 00:54:59.240
So that's a thing.

00:54:59.240 --> 00:55:00.820
A beautiful thing.

00:55:00.820 --> 00:55:04.370
Burial. You're right,
you're right.

00:55:04.370 --> 00:55:06.830
The fertilizer is good.

00:55:06.830 --> 00:55:09.900
It wasn't a gang of dullard
came up with chucking a fish

00:55:09.900 --> 00:55:12.260
in the planting hole or
some midwife got lucky

00:55:12.260 --> 00:55:13.560
with the placenta.

00:55:13.560 --> 00:55:15.280
Oh, I'll plant a tree here.

00:55:15.280 --> 00:55:19.070
And a sudden flush of quince
and jam enough for months.

00:55:19.070 --> 00:55:23.800
Yes, the magic dust our bodies
become cast spells on the roots

00:55:23.800 --> 00:55:27.220
about which someone else could
tell you the chemical processes,

00:55:27.220 --> 00:55:31.080
but it's just magic to me, which
is why a couple springs ago

00:55:31.080 --> 00:55:33.940
when first put it in my
two bare root plum trees

00:55:33.940 --> 00:55:38.860
out back I took the jar which
has become my father's house

00:55:38.860 --> 00:55:42.620
and lonely for him and hoping
to coax him back for my mother

00:55:42.620 --> 00:55:47.110
as much as me, poured some
of him in the planting holes.

00:55:47.110 --> 00:55:50.250
And he dove in, glad
for the robust air,

00:55:50.250 --> 00:55:53.360
saddling a slight gust
into my nose and mouth,

00:55:53.360 --> 00:55:55.380
chuckling as I coughed.

00:55:55.380 --> 00:55:59.190
But mostly he disappeared into
the minor yawns in the earth,

00:55:59.190 --> 00:56:03.850
into which I placed the trees,
splaying wide their roots

00:56:03.850 --> 00:56:05.260
and casting the gray dust

00:56:05.260 --> 00:56:08.450
of my old man evenly
throughout the hole,

00:56:08.450 --> 00:56:12.160
replacing then the clods
of dense Indiana soil

00:56:12.160 --> 00:56:17.370
until the roots and my father
were buried, watering it all

00:56:17.370 --> 00:56:20.920
in with one hand while holding
the tree with the other straight

00:56:20.920 --> 00:56:23.680
as the flag to the
nation of simple joy,

00:56:23.680 --> 00:56:27.380
of which my father is now
a naturalized citizen.

00:56:27.380 --> 00:56:31.240
Waving the flag from
his subterranean lair.

00:56:31.240 --> 00:56:35.280
The roots curled around him
like shawls or jungle gyms,

00:56:35.280 --> 00:56:39.310
like hookahs or the arms of
ancestors before breast stroking

00:56:39.310 --> 00:56:42.990
into the xylem, riding the
elevator up through the cambium

00:56:42.990 --> 00:56:47.470
and into the leaves where when
you put you ear close enough you

00:56:47.470 --> 00:56:49.340
can hear him whisper.

00:56:49.340 --> 00:56:50.900
Good morning.

00:56:50.900 --> 00:56:52.900
Where if you close your eyes

00:56:52.900 --> 00:56:56.120
and push your face you can
feel his stubbly jowls,

00:56:56.120 --> 00:56:58.170
and good Lord, this
year he was giddy

00:56:58.170 --> 00:57:02.600
at the first real fruit set and
nestled into the 30 or 40 plums

00:57:02.600 --> 00:57:05.750
in the two trees, peering
out from the sweet meat

00:57:05.750 --> 00:57:08.510
with his hands pressed
against the purple skin,

00:57:08.510 --> 00:57:10.800
like cathedral glass.

00:57:10.800 --> 00:57:15.000
And imagine his joy as the sun
wizarded forth those abundant

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:18.110
sugars, and I plodded
barefoot and prayerful

00:57:18.110 --> 00:57:22.240
at the first ripe plum swell
and blush, almost weepy,

00:57:22.240 --> 00:57:24.610
conjuring some surely
ponderous verse

00:57:24.610 --> 00:57:26.230
to convey this bottomless grace.

00:57:26.230 --> 00:57:29.190
You know, oh father, oh
father kind of stuff.

00:57:29.190 --> 00:57:33.410
Hundreds of hot air balloons
filling the sky in my chest.

00:57:33.410 --> 00:57:35.790
We're placing his
intubated body,

00:57:35.790 --> 00:57:39.240
listing like a boat
keel side up.

00:57:39.240 --> 00:57:42.690
Replacing the steady stream
of water from the one eye,

00:57:42.690 --> 00:57:46.100
which his brother wiped
before removing the tube.

00:57:46.100 --> 00:57:48.650
Keeping his hand on the
forehead until the last wind,

00:57:48.650 --> 00:57:51.040
and his body wandered off,

00:57:51.040 --> 00:57:53.920
while my brother
wailed like an animal.

00:57:53.920 --> 00:57:58.420
And my mother said,
weeping, it's okay.

00:57:58.420 --> 00:57:59.720
It's okay.

00:57:59.720 --> 00:58:01.100
You can go honey.

00:58:01.100 --> 00:58:03.550
At all of which my
father guffawed,

00:58:03.550 --> 00:58:07.390
by kicking from the first
buckets of juice down my chin,

00:58:07.390 --> 00:58:09.740
staining one of my two
button-down shirts,

00:58:09.740 --> 00:58:15.080
the salmon-colored silk one,
hollering, there's more of that.

00:58:15.080 --> 00:58:19.800
Almost dancing now,
the plum in the tree.

00:58:19.800 --> 00:58:24.460
The way he did as a person,
bent over and biting his lip

00:58:24.460 --> 00:58:26.950
and chucking the one hip
out and then the other

00:58:26.950 --> 00:58:31.450
with his elbows cocked and fists
loosely made and eyes closed

00:58:31.450 --> 00:58:34.690
and mouth made trumpet when he
knew he could make you happy,

00:58:34.690 --> 00:58:38.300
just by being a little
silly and sweet.

00:58:39.510 --> 00:58:47.170
[ Applause ]

00:58:47.170 --> 00:58:48.650
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: That's
just perfect.

00:58:48.650 --> 00:58:53.790
That's not a poem you can write
in the grips of fresh grief.

00:58:53.790 --> 00:58:55.090
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:58:55.090 --> 00:58:56.390
Yeah, that's right,
that's right.

00:58:56.390 --> 00:58:57.690
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: That's
grief resolved.

00:58:57.690 --> 00:58:58.990
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, yeah.

00:58:58.990 --> 00:59:00.290
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Transformed.

00:59:00.290 --> 00:59:01.590
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Transformed, yeah.

00:59:01.590 --> 00:59:02.890
Yeah, and the garden sort

00:59:02.890 --> 00:59:04.190
of modeled how we
might do that, for me.

00:59:04.190 --> 00:59:05.490
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It's
very lovely.

00:59:05.490 --> 00:59:06.790
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: Yeah, thank you.

00:59:06.790 --> 00:59:09.090
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Very lovely.

00:59:13.130 --> 00:59:16.930
In the title poem of
your latest collection,

00:59:16.930 --> 00:59:19.130
Catalog of Unabashed
Gratitude, you write,

00:59:19.130 --> 00:59:23.160
I can't stop my gratitude,
which includes dear reader, you,

00:59:23.160 --> 00:59:24.880
for staying here with me,

00:59:24.880 --> 00:59:28.240
for moving your lips
just so as I speak.

00:59:28.240 --> 00:59:31.090
I want so badly to rub
the sponge of gratitude

00:59:31.090 --> 00:59:36.260
over every last thing.

00:59:36.260 --> 00:59:37.850
Why is gratitude so
important to you,

00:59:37.850 --> 00:59:40.030
or why has it become
so important to you?

00:59:40.030 --> 00:59:47.160
&gt;&gt; Ross Gay: You know, I've
been trying to think about that,

00:59:48.290 --> 00:59:52.680
like, I mean obviously it's
sort of this, as I'm reading all

00:59:52.680 --> 00:59:55.460
of these poems, it's this
think I'm sort of like arriving

00:59:55.460 --> 01:00:00.620
at over years of sort
of thinking and study.

01:00:00.620 --> 01:00:05.310
But I think, like thinking
about that heaven poem,

01:00:05.310 --> 01:00:07.500
it's like what am I working
out there, like working

01:00:07.500 --> 01:00:12.540
out like how do you sort
of deal with all of it,

01:00:12.540 --> 01:00:15.250
like sort of just sort
of be with all of it.

01:00:15.250 --> 01:00:24.670
And but then there's this,
this thing in that Catalog poem

01:00:24.670 --> 01:00:29.210
where I, I sort of, you know,
I want to practice this thing

01:00:29.210 --> 01:00:34.280
of acknowledgement, that one,
that we are not here long

01:00:34.280 --> 01:00:36.910
if we're, you know,
we're not here long.

01:00:36.910 --> 01:00:39.500
And so there is this
kind of preciousness

01:00:39.500 --> 01:00:44.180
that no matter what
it's fleeting, you know,

01:00:44.180 --> 01:00:47.230
and it's passing, and you are
passing, and I am passing,

01:00:47.230 --> 01:00:50.320
and that, I think we're
more likely, if we're sort

01:00:50.320 --> 01:00:51.620
of with that, we're more likely

01:00:51.620 --> 01:00:54.400
to love each other
actually, you know.

01:00:54.400 --> 01:00:57.590
And then I think of this, I've
been thinking about like what,

01:00:57.590 --> 01:01:00.360
I had this card, I mean I
do letter press printing,

01:01:00.360 --> 01:01:05.540
and I made these cards with
the word interdepend on them.

01:01:05.540 --> 01:01:11.260
And I gave, I gave one to a
friend, and she was like, yeah,

01:01:11.260 --> 01:01:15.380
that's, that can be hard
work, hard to do, you know.

01:01:15.380 --> 01:01:18.660
And I was like, right, and
sort of thinking about it,

01:01:18.660 --> 01:01:27.520
and I was thinking, like
among the sorrows or mistakes

01:01:27.520 --> 01:01:30.460
or failures of the
imagination again is to,

01:01:30.460 --> 01:01:34.740
is to not understand
or not believe

01:01:34.740 --> 01:01:38.450
that we are fundamentally
interdependent, you know.

01:01:38.450 --> 01:01:43.090
And when I say we, I mean the
grand we, meaning the water,

01:01:43.090 --> 01:01:47.600
you know, meaning the air,
meaning the trees, you know.

01:01:47.600 --> 01:01:51.340
Everything is interdependent,
and that is like,

01:01:51.340 --> 01:01:56.330
and I feel like, you
know, when you celebrate,

01:01:56.330 --> 01:01:58.820
and it just occurred to me like,
you know, maybe I'm slow coming

01:01:58.820 --> 01:02:03.640
to this, but when you celebrate
the winter equinox say,

01:02:03.640 --> 01:02:10.150
you're saying to the earth,
etc., if you're so gracious

01:02:10.150 --> 01:02:16.250
as to come back, Summer, that
would be awesome, you know.

01:02:16.250 --> 01:02:18.290
[laughter] Which is like
a real thing to say.

01:02:18.290 --> 01:02:25.750
Like if you are so gracious to
rain again or to stop raining

01:02:25.750 --> 01:02:31.200
or however it is, if you're
so gracious as to grow things.

01:02:31.200 --> 01:02:34.190
And it strikes me that
the more, the more I think

01:02:34.190 --> 01:02:37.250
about gratitude, the more I'm
thinking that like, you know,

01:02:37.250 --> 01:02:39.210
because there's like
gratitude about like, yeah,

01:02:39.210 --> 01:02:40.690
I got a nice pair of
shoes, I'm grateful,

01:02:40.690 --> 01:02:43.850
like that's, who
cares, you know.

01:02:43.850 --> 01:02:47.390
When I'm talking about
gratitude, I think,

01:02:47.390 --> 01:02:52.070
the more I sort of try to
put it together in my head,

01:02:52.070 --> 01:02:56.720
I'm talking about the
understanding of this

01:02:56.720 --> 01:03:00.010
like undeniable
interconnectedness

01:03:00.010 --> 01:03:03.680
and interdependence actually,
and I think that's thing

01:03:03.680 --> 01:03:07.600
that we are utterly
necessary to one another.

01:03:07.600 --> 01:03:11.440
And again, like the one
another is the big one another,

01:03:11.440 --> 01:03:14.800
and I feel like if you, if
you think of it like that,

01:03:14.800 --> 01:03:20.040
it is like, it conjures
and it requires gratitude.

01:03:20.040 --> 01:03:22.260
It requires gratitude, you know.

01:03:22.260 --> 01:03:25.880
But if you think, I'm in charge
of the water because I turn it

01:03:25.880 --> 01:03:29.950
on and I pay the bill, it's
like that's a fucking joke.

01:03:29.950 --> 01:03:33.410
That's a joke.

01:03:33.410 --> 01:03:35.810
See. [laughter]

01:03:35.810 --> 01:03:37.910
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: From
the mouth of babes.

01:03:37.910 --> 01:03:47.170
[laughter] You knew I was
